# Document a Module

> **Thesis:** Use this when documenting an existing module. `plan-feature.mdc`
> plans forward. This documents backward ‚Äî capturing what was built, why, and
> how it behaves.

## Order of Operations

1. **Schema first** ‚Äî read the migrations in `backend/migrations/` to understand tables, enums, relationships, indexes
2. **Service logic** ‚Äî read `backend/internal/service/<module>/*.go` for business rules, auth checks, transactions, status transitions
3. **Handler surface** ‚Äî read `backend/internal/handler/*.go` for request validation, response shapes, route registration in `backend/internal/wire/routes.go`
4. **Frontend routes** ‚Äî read `frontend/src/routes/(private)/*.tsx` for pages, modals, state management
5. **Write the spec** ‚Äî fill the template below

## Evidence Standards

- Every business rule must be marked:
  - `[Verified: service/item/item.go, Create()]` ‚Äî symbol citation (preferred in module specs)
  - `[Verified: service/item/item.go:142]` ‚Äî line citation (checked by `check_citation_freshness.sh`)
  - `[NEEDS VERIFICATION]` ‚Äî inferred from naming or partial evidence
- Do NOT invent business rules. If you can't confirm it, mark it unverified.
- Use concrete evidence: function names, line numbers, SQL column names, enum values

## Spec Template

```markdown
# Module: [Name]

> **Thesis:** [One sentence ‚Äî what this module does and why it exists]

| | |
|---|---|
| **Domain** | [e.g., Core, Billing, User Management] |
| **Complexity** | Low / Medium / High / Critical |
| **Status** | Complete / In Progress / Not Started |

---

## Scope

**Includes:**
- [entities, services, handlers this spec covers]

**Excludes:**
- [what belongs in other module specs]

**Depends On:**
- [other modules referenced by FK or service call]

---

