## Complexity Ratings

| Rating | Criteria |
|--------|----------|
| Low | < 500 lines, simple CRUD, no state machine |
| Medium | 500-1,500 lines, has state machine or moderate rules |
| High | 1,500-3,000 lines, complex state machines, financial calcs |
| Critical | 3,000+ lines, polymorphic entities, cross-system deps |

## Output

Save to `docs/modules/{module}/spec.md`. Create the directory if it doesn't exist.

**After updating a spec,** check `docs/permissions.md` if endpoint auth logic changed.

## After Writing

Run `@audit-codebase` against the spec to verify:

1. Every FK dependency has a Depends On entry
2. Every Scope Includes item has matching content
3. Business rules cite actual file paths
4. No `[NEEDS VERIFICATION]` items that can be resolved from code

## Same-Commit Spec Sync

When code changes a documented contract (state machine transition, enum value, business rule, side effect, API shape), update the spec **in the same commit**. Spec drift is the single largest source of doc rot in this repo.

What counts as "documented contract":

- A row in the State Machine table.
- An enum literal listed under Entities.
- A bullet under Business Rules with `[Verified: ...]`.
- A side effect listed under Side Effects (email, webhook, SSE event).
- A row in the API Surface table.
- A Tests entry describing handler/service coverage for a module endpoint.

If the spec doesn't mention the thing you changed, update the **Tests** section when handler or service test files change ‚Äî `check_spec_drift.sh` flags any handler/service edit without a matching spec touch.

To verify before committing: `scripts/check_spec_drift.sh <base-ref>`. If the change legitimately does not affect module behavior, include `[skip-spec(<module>): <one-line reason>]` in the commit message, or `[skip-spec: <reason>]` to skip all modules. See `ci-workflow` "Spec-Drift Gate".

## Anti-Rationalization

| Excuse | Counter |
|---|---|
| "I'll update the spec in a follow-up doc commit" | CI `spec-drift` job fails the PR. Sync in the same commit costs 30 seconds. |
| "The spec is auto-generated from code" | It isn't. Specs are hand-written narrative + `[Verified:]` annotations. |
| "The change is too small to matter to the spec" | Handler/service file changes always require a spec touch or `[skip-spec(...)]` ‚Äî the drift script is path-based, not semantic. |
| "Someone will catch it in audit" | They will ‚Äî that's the CI failure you're trying to avoid. |
